<title type="html"><![CDATA[different kind of hardware request - Nintendo in car]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6546&amp;p=63507#p63507"><![CDATA[
If you'd rather use windows, you could look into "arcade frontends" or something similar (more often used for the MAME emulator, but most of them support other emulators).<br /><br />It took a little bit of tweaking stuff (and edits in the registry as well), but I installed TinyXP and a front-end called MALA on my old PC that I put into an arcade cabinet.  It boots very fast, looks great in the menu (using a skin someone made, I forget what it's called), and other than the BIOS screen at power-up (which I guess could be hide-able too on most mainboards) you can't even tell it's in windows PC unless you exit the front-end program.  And it's all controllable with a joystick and a few buttons.  Usually the only problem is the (highly annoying) requirement of having to press alt+F4 to exit most windows programs.  So you need a way to map a button (or combination of buttons) to that.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Wed Jun 30, 2010 9:52 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
