<div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">To be 100% legal, you have to build a CopyNES and dump your own Game Paks.<br /></div><br />Honestly, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ROM_image#Private_ownership" class="postlink">I don't think that's legal either</a>.</div><br />The link you gave mentions <em>Atari v. JS&amp;A</em>, which referred to archival copies under <a href="http://www.bitlaw.com/source/17usc/117.html" class="postlink">17 USC 117(a)(2)</a>, not adaptations under 117(a)(1). I read some of the materials around this case, and it didn't appear to mention 117(a)(1)'s allowance for dumps "created as an essential step in the utilization of the computer program in conjunction with a machine and [...] used in no other manner".<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Jun 30, 2010 8:43 am</p><hr />
